{
    "analysis": "The prior result shows that metric anomalies in the incident window are heavily concentrated on adservice: the top-20 component-KPIs with anomalies are all adservice KPIs (JVM memory/GC, gRPC/http metrics). Each of those KPI series shows a small number of anomalies in-window (typically 2 points above global P95 and 2 points below global P5 out of 30 samples). This indicates adservice experienced several brief excursions during the 03:00–03:30 window. However, those per-KPI anomaly counts alone do not yet establish a fault (consecutive sub-series) nor the exact root cause time. We need to check whether many KPIs for adservice were anomalous at the same timestamps (coincident multi-KPI anomalies), which would indicate a stronger fault event and give the earliest occurrence time. We also should check whether any other components show similar coincident anomaly bursts.\n\nNext step: compute anomaly flags per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) against their global P95/P5 (global computed over full metric series), then aggregate by cmdb_id and timestamp (within the incident window) to count how many KPIs were anomalous at each timestamp. Return the top groups (component + timestamp) by anomaly count and a per-component total anomaly count across the window. This will help pinpoint the most likely root-cause component and the earliest timestamp where many resources deviated together.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv do the following and return compact results: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and global P5 from the full metric series. 2) Filter rows to the incident window 2022-03-21 03:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 03:30:00+08:00. 3) For each filtered row, mark it as anomalous_above if value > global_p95, anomalous_below if value < global_p5; treat either as anomalous. 4) Aggregate anomalous rows by (cmdb_id, timestamp_local) and produce a top-20 table sorted by anomaly_count desc with these columns: cmdb_id, timestamp_local, anomaly_count (number of distinct kpi_name anomalous at that timestamp), total_kpi_points_at_that_timestamp (total metric kpis recorded for that cmdb_id at that timestamp), top_5_kpis_anomalous (comma-separated kpi_name list limited to 5), sample_values (for those top kpis include their metric values). 5) Also produce a compact per-cmdb_id summary (top 10) giving total_anomaly_count_in_window and earliest_anomaly_timestamp_local. Keep outputs bounded (top-20 and top-10). Store intermediate tables for later steps but do not print raw series."
}

Reviewing the analysis: metrics, traces, and error logs all point to the frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2) showing the earliest and strongest concurrent anomalies starting at the window start; traces from frontends show duration spikes with paired row_count drops and repeated warning messages (“failed to retrieve...”), consistent with network-level request failures. Therefore the most likely single root cause is at the frontend service level and began at the start of the incident window, caused by container-level packet loss.

